  "input": "HDJ RE-hospitalization report\nThe child Amroun Abdel Aziz, aged 09 from Chlef and residing in Oran, followed in our department since 01/11/2021 for a primary immunodeficiency type \"Wiskott Aldrich syndrome\", complicated by dilation of the cylindrical DDB bronchi and chronic respiratory failure stage 1. Admitted on 03/12/2026 for his treatment 53 immunoglobulins\nHistory of illness:\nMain diagnosis: Wiskott Aldrich type DIP\nDate of diagnosis: 12/11/2020\nAge of diagnosis: 04 years and 9 months\nAssociated diagnoses: Dilation of the cylindrical bronchi\nChronic respiratory failure stage 1\nDiagnostic elements:\nAnamnestics\n-Male gender\n-Repeated respiratory infections\n-Several outbreaks of eczema. Clinic\n-Anemic syndrome consisting of: mucocutaneous pallor. -Skin hemorrhagic syndrome such as petechiae spread to the face and trunk. -Eczema lesions on the face and lower limbs. Para-clinical:\n-Bi cytopenia; anemia, thrombocytopenia\n- Assessment of primary immunodeficiency: 12/29/2020, Profound reduction in the expression of the WASp protein results in favor of DIP Wiskott Aldrich syndrome\nImmunoglobulin treatment at a rate of 0.8mg1/kg/4h at the SAP each month. Last dose received: 02/09/2026 (0.8g/kg)\nLast update made in May 2025\nHISTORY OF HOSPITALIZATIONS\nANAMNESIS 03/12/2026\nEvents since the last visit: 02/09/2026\nConsultation: no\nOn the respiratory level: wet cough, clear sputum,\nOcularly: Conjunctival hyperemia, following ocular trauma on 03/10/2026\nHematologically: No hemorrhage\nPreserved appetite\nUnder ambulatory oxygen therapy\nSchooled\nProcessing in progress:\nAzithromycin 1 day out of 02\nBactrim 25mg/kg/d\nItraconazole 05mg/kg/day: 02 times/day\nPulmicort 1mg: 02 times/day\nNebulization with hypertonic salt serum\nRespiratory physiotherapy done by the mother\nWell-kept notebooks\nAssessments made:\nECBC: Candida Albicans released on 02/15/2026\nIgG rate: 02/08/2026: 8.24g/l\nCLINICAL EXAMINATION UPON ADMISSION: Date: 03/12/2026\nAnthropometric measurements:\nWeight: 27.1 kg [-1.1 DS] Height: 132 cm [-1.2 DS] BMI: 15.6 kg/m2 (-0.9) Normal\nGeneral condition preserved, conscious, T: 37.2\nSkin examination: no cutaneous and mucosal hemorrhagic syndrome, dry skin, multiple scars on the lower limbs\nPleuropulmonary examination: FR: 38c/min SPo2: 96% Under 1 liter of O2, slight signs of struggle. Thoracic keel deformity, clubbing\n. Auscultation of polymorphic rales\nCardiovascular examination: HR: 98 bpm, Auscultation: no murmur/no added noises\nOphthalmic examination: Conjunctival hyperemia of the left eye, normal right eye\nAbdominal examination: flexible transit preserved, no organomegaly\nENT examination: Presence of dental caries\nExamination of other devices without anomalies\nParaclinical assessment upon admission: 03/12/2026\nFNS: WBC: 7400 elements/ul (PNN: 5700 Lymph: 1200) Hb: 10.6 g/dl Platelet: 90,000 elements/ul\nCRP: negative TQ: 15.6 Sec TP: 69.6% TCK: 30 Sec\nSupport:\n-Hospitalization\n- Conditioning, peripheral venous route\n-Replacement immunotherapy: IV infusion at 0.8g/kg or 20g, to be administered over 4 hours (Intratect)\n-Monitoring\n- Ophthalmic opinion made: AV: Right and left eye: 10/10 Conjunctival hyperemia of the left eye with transparent cornea, tearing suggesting viral conjunctivitis, child placed on Tobrex eye drops and eye wash by SSI. The immunoglobulin treatment passed without incident\nSame day release\nContinue the same treatment: bactrim antibiotic prophylaxis and itraconazole antifungal\nZithromax, Pulmicort\nPhysiotherapy and saline nebulizations\nHygiene-dietary advice and notebook keeping\nControl appointment: 04/12/2026 for immunoglobulin treatment\nTo collect / To do:\nNext immunoglobulin treatment appointment is scheduled for 04/14/2026\nPlan an ECBC to recover before the next treatment\nPlan a chest CT,\nSchedule an abdominopelvic ultrasound\nSchedule an echocardiogram\nStomato advice (dental caries)\nRetrieve the health record\nSibling screening\nDepartment resident: Dr Djoudi Department assistant: Dr Khelil",
  "target": "Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome",
